Struggling to create a visually appealing and impactful presentation? Don't worry, you're not alone. But fret no more, because presentation templates are here to save the day!

What are presentation templates?

Think of presentation templates as pre-designed layouts that provide a solid foundation for your content. They come equipped with pre-formatted slides, stylish fonts, and professional graphics, saving you valuable time and effort.

Why use presentation templates?

Here are just a few reasons why you should ditch the blank canvas and embrace the power of presentation templates:

Save Time: Templates eliminate the need to design your presentation from scratch, freeing you to focus on developing your content.
Professional Appearance: Templates offer a polished and professional look that will impress your audience.
Consistency: Templates ensure consistency in your presentation's design, making it visually cohesive and engaging.
Variety of Choices: There's a template out there for every need and occasion, from business proposals to educational lectures.
Easy Customization: Most templates are easily customizable, allowing you to personalize them with your own branding and content.

ðThis is One of the popular street food of MADURAI. This Mullu Murungai keerai is best for cold , cold and sore throat. And this is of the traditional recipe of Saurashtra people. 

A quick recipe 
âSoak 1&1/2 cup rice ( can use idli rice / raw rice) 1/4 cup urad dal for 3 hours.
âWash & Remove all the veins from the Mullu Murungai keerai( kalyana murungai/ Indian coral tree) and chop it into small pieces 
âNow drain the water and add soaked rice, urad dal,1/2 tbsp pepper,1/4 tbsp cumin, 4-5 garlic, salt and chopped leaves in a mixer & blend it to a coarse thick paste.
âNow add salt & 1&1/2 tbsp rice flour and start kneading the dough.
âYour dough should be soft and more like a chapathi dough.(if dough is sticky then you can increase the amount of rice flour) 
âNow add oil to a working mat and flatten your dough in circular shape.(your poori should not be thin)
âHeat oil and deep fry it. ( Your vadai should puff up as poori)
âFlip and cook both the sides.
âNow for the spicy powder- To a pan add 1 tbsp urad dal, 1/4 tsp pepper, 1/4 tsp cumin and roast it.
âThen add 1 red chilli sautÃ© for few seconds and turn of the flame.
âThen add 3 tbsp Bengal gram, salt, asafoetida 1/4 tsp and grind it to a coarse powder.
âNow add it your Vadai and serve hot.

Love can be a beautiful and transformative experience, but it can also bring immense pain when it's unrequited. We've all been there, pouring our hearts out to someone who doesn't share the same feelings. It's like a slow agony, a feeling of dying a little inside every day.

Loving someone deeply, only to have our love go unreciprocated, can be one of the most challenging and heart-wrenching experiences we face. Yet, in the midst of this pain, we must remember that our capacity to love is a gift. It's a testament to our vulnerability, compassion, and willingness to open our hearts, even in the face of potential heartbreak.

While it may feel like we're dying inside, this experience can also teach us valuable lessons about resilience, self-worth, and the complexity of human emotions. It reminds us that love cannot be forced or demanded, but rather it flows naturally when two hearts align.

So, as we navigate the pain of unrequited love, let us also embrace the strength within us. Let us cherish the beauty of our own hearts and the capacity to love fiercely. And may we find solace in knowing that our journey, though painful, will ultimately lead us to the love and happiness we truly deserve.
